      <hedline>
        <hl1>Benjamin's Views</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Donald Brackett letter disputes Richard B Woodward's April 23 article on fakery in art</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Walter Benjamin never celebrated photography for having ''boldly done away with the 'aura' of an original,'' as Mr. Woodward imagines. Far from it, Benjamin referred often to the ''decay of the aura,'' to its ''withering away'' in the grasp of mechanical contrivance, to the shift from cult ritual for unique viewing and an inevitable descent into mere ''exhibition value.'' Though Benjamin was obviously not opposed to photography per se, he certainly never intended his thoughts to be bent into the shape which Mr. Woodward gives them.</p>
        <p>DONALD BRACKETT  Toronto</p>
      </block>
